.TH socketpair 3SOCKET "10 Jan 2001" "SunOS 5.11" "Sockets Library Functions"
.SH NAME
socketpair \- create a pair of connected sockets
.SH SYNOPSIS
.LP
.nf
\fBcc\fR [ \fIflag\fR .\|.\|. ] \fIfile\fR .\|.\|. \fB-lsocket\fR \fB -lnsl \fR [ \fIlibrary\fR .\|.\|. ]
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/socket.h>

\fBint\fR \fBsocketpair\fR(\fBint\fR \fIdomain\fR, \fBint\fR \fItype\fR, \fBint\fR \fIprotocol\fR, \fBint\fR \fIsv\fR[2]);
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
.LP
The
.B socketpair()
library call creates an unnamed pair of connected
sockets in the specified address family
.IR domain ,
of the specified
.IR type ,
that uses the optionally specified
.IR protocol .
The
descriptors that are used in referencing the new sockets are returned in
\fIsv\fR[0] and \fIsv\fR[1]. The two sockets are indistinguishable.
.SH RETURN VALUES
.sp
.LP
.B socketpair()
returns \fB\(mi1\fR on failure and
.B 0
on success.
.SH ERRORS
.sp
.LP
The call succeeds unless:
.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B EAFNOSUPPORT
.ad
.RS 19n
.rt
The specified address family is not supported on this machine.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B EMFILE
.ad
.RS 19n
.rt
Too many descriptors are in use by this process.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B ENOMEM
.ad
.RS 19n
.rt
There was insufficient user memory for the operation to complete.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B ENOSR
.ad
.RS 19n
.rt
There were insufficient
.B STREAMS
resources for the operation to
complete.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B EOPNOTSUPP
.ad
.RS 19n
.rt
The specified protocol does not support creation of socket pairs.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B EPROTONOSUPPORT
.ad
.RS 19n
.rt
The specified protocol is not supported on this machine.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
.B EACCES
.ad
.RS 19n
.rt
The process does not have appropriate privileges.
.RE

